Here’s another tutorial series… this one is called, making a giant “show stopper” Marble.  The first step is making a fume trapped UV core. I spin up some eclipse black and then I cover it with radioactive UV yellow.  I then spray on some silver, melt it in and then spray on some gold. I then do a quick clear sleeve on the lathe.  A quick word about this technique.  I first saw this effect on a snodgrass chillum I had in 1993.  I was very interested in the look and I couldn’t figure out how it was done until I did it by accident in 1998. I wasn’t very good. at sleeving yet and and I did it here in there with a clear but the technique didn’t really develop for me until a couple years later when I started doing it over black. I called it atmosphere and this was before anyone started doing space tech.  I really enjoyed Josh Simpson soft glass marbles back then and this was the closest I could get to his vibe.  Stay tuned for the next video where I start building the first layer of buildings.. thank you to my friend @didyclips for hooking me up with this awesome GoPro filter.

So part two of making a giant Marble is preparing the core for sleeving by adding some very clean pre-stripped clear to either end.  I take a big chunk of 45mm clear rod, and I strip off about 2 mm of the outer surface so it’s super clean and then I add some to either end of the fumed core. Shout out to @didyclips for the GoPro filter. I couldn’t make this video without it.

In the third video of “making a giant Marble”, I am preparing the opal and then adding the first layer of buildings.  I then move over to my trusty machine and add the second sleeve.  The next step is where I add the most artwork. 🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻 hope everyone is having fun today.

Part four of making a giant marble. I am preparing the colored foreground for the second layer of artwork going in and putting it on and cleaning it up then getting ready to add castles in trees next.. Making this video reminds me how long and sometimes tedious this processes is.  For some reason it usually goes pretty fast in my mind though and it’s well worth it to make something unique. 🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻😉😉 stay warm out there.

Part five of making a giant marble.  I had to try to pack a lot in on this one but basically I’m adding the castles, trees, flowers, mushrooms and a signature cane then doing another quick sleeve and then adding one more layer of the buildings on the outside before I put it in the kiln.  Wow, a lot of steps. 💯💯

Part 6 of making a giant marble. This is basically the final sleeve and the final shaping. I had to use the chest mount because the camera would’ve gotten too hot mounted stationary by the lathe.  It’s still actually got too hot on my chest, so mounted it at the back of my bench.  This was a long video so I had to chop it up quite a bit but I think you get the vibe.  Shout out to @didyclips for the awesome GoPro filter that made this all possible. In the next video, I will show the final product.. 🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻

Here is how I make a skyline murrine.  Start with a clear core and make it into a square. Put a layer of UV pink around the square. Flatten it out and then put a layer of lotus white over that. Flatten that out and then cone down either end to the diameter that I’m going to pull it out to.  Pull it out let it cool and then cut the ends off on the saw in the morning. This is basically going to be one style of windows in one of the buildings. I have to do this a bunch more times and then put it all together and make some palm trees and some accessories.  And then I will have a new South Beach skyline to work with for the summer.. hopefully. If all goes well. 🤞🏻🤞🏻🤞🏻
